The worshippers of Gaesar have recognized this and, having canonized him as a saint for qualities which are not smintly, they have compounded with their scruples by ascribing to him other qualities, which are, but which he did not in any great measure possess. In ad- dition to genius he is said to have been possessed with a love of clemency. Such clemency, as he had, did not possess him : he possessed it : he never let it master him or interfere with other objects. Pity with him rarely rose to an emution, never to apassion. It was intellec- tual so to speak rather than moral.
